E LINE CHART\":\"Example of Simple Line Charts: Give an example that shows a gentle increase in the sales trend over five years. By contrast, give another example of simple line chart that shows a more significant rate of change in total sales.\"", "\"MULTIPLE LINE CHART\":\"Example of Multiple Line Chart: draw a multiple line chart with two lines: one is for the Total sales, and the other for the Total costs. The Total sales is in blue color, and the Total costs in red color. The y-axis is not from the origin. The smaller scale means that the rate of change in the lines appears more significant. The gap between the lines is profit. The narrowing of the gap in 20X2 and 20X3 means that profit is shrinking. It is easy to see the sales and cost trends and how they compare.\"", "\"PIE CHARTS\":\"Pie charts are most suitable for showing the proportions of multiple data series at a single period or point. The entire \\\"pie\\\" is 100%, with each data series representing a proportion of it. For example, 25% would be a quarter of the pie.\"", "\"EXAMPLE OF SCATTER DIAGRAM\":\"The total monthly costs and outputs for a process are as follows: Jan 100 units, $2,500; Feb 110 units, $2,600; Mar 90 units, $2,200; Apr 100 units, $2,600; May 100 units, $2,550; Jun 130 units, $3,000; Jul 110 units, $2,650; Aug 90 units, $2,300; Sep 120 units, $2,800; Oct 130 units, $2,900; Nov 140 units, $2,950; Dec 100 units, $2,400. Plotting the pairs of data gives the following scatter diagram: There appears to be a relationship between output units and total costs (more output, higher cost), although some cost variations occur at some of the output levels. Where there appears to be a linear relationship between two variables, a trend can be estimated using a \\\"line of best fit\\\".\"", "\"INAPPROPRIATE USE OF DATA VISUALISATION\":\"It is essential to use the proper visualisation to convey the appropriate meaning to the user. The wrong type of chart will be misleading and may lead to dysfunctional decision-making.\"", "\"INFORMATION SYSTEM\":\"An information system is an integrated set of components that collect, store, process and communicate information.\"", "\"CONTROL PROCEDURES FOR DATA SECURITY\":\"Control procedures to ensure the security of confidential data typically include physical and logical access controls, passwords, encryption, systems logs and audit trails.\"", "\"SOURCES OF INFORMATION\":\"Sources of information are: Internal (e.g. transaction processing systems); and External, which may be primary (e.g. market research) or secondary (e.g. government statistics).\"", "\"HISTOGRAM\":\"A histogram is a type of bar chart that represents the frequency distribution of a set of continuous or discrete data.\"", "\"AREA CHARTS\":\"Area charts are used to represent cumulative totals over time using numbers or percentages.\"", "\"BUBBLE CHARTS\":\"Bubble charts are used to display three dimensions of data. Each point is represented by a bubble, with the position on the x and y axes representing two dimensions and the size of the bubble representing the third dimension.\"", "\"HEAT MAPS\":\"Heat maps use color to represent data values in a matrix. They are useful for showing the magnitude of data and patterns.\"", "\"TREE MAPS\":\"Tree maps display hierarchical data using nested rectangles. The size and color of the rectangles can represent different dimensions of the data.\"", "\"RADAR CHARTS\":\"Radar charts are used to display multivariate data in the form of a two-dimensional chart of three or more quantitative variables represented on axes starting from the same point.\""], "parameters": {"model": "text-embedding-3-small", "temperature": 0.0, "frequency_penalty": null, "presence_penalty": null, "top_p": 1.0, "max_tokens": 4000, "n": 1}}